t: Psalm 104
Bless*p the Lord,*s O my soul. O Lord*s my God, thou art very great; thou art clothed with honour and majesty.
Who*p coverest thyself with light as with a garment: who stretchest out the heavens like a curtain:
Who*p layeth the beams of his chambers in the waters: who maketh the clouds his chariot: who walketh upon the wings of the wind:
Who*p maketh his angels spirits; his ministers a flaming fire:
Who*p laid the foundations of the earth, that it should not be removed for ever.
Thou*p coveredst it with the deep as with a garment: the waters stood above the mountains.
At*p thy rebuke they fled; at the voice of thy thunder they hasted away.
They*p go up by the mountains; they go down by the valleys unto the place which thou hast founded for them.
Thou*p hast set a bound that they may not pass over; that they turn not again to cover the earth.
He*p sendeth the springs into the valleys, which run among the hills.
They*p give drink to every beast of the field: the wild asses quench their thirst.
By*p them shall the fowls of the heaven have their habitation, which sing among the branches.
He*p watereth the hills from his chambers: the earth is satisfied with the fruit of thy works.

The*p trees of the Lord*s are full of sap; the cedars of Lebanon, which he hath planted;

The*p high hills are a refuge for the wild goats; and the rocks for the conies.
He*p appointed the moon for seasons: the sun knoweth his going down.

The*p sun ariseth, they gather themselves together, and lay them down in their dens.

O*p Lord,*s how manifold are thy works! in wisdom hast thou made them all: the earth is full of thy riches.
So*p is this great and wide sea, wherein are things creeping innumerable, both small and great beasts.
There*p go the ships: there is that leviathan, whom thou hast made to play therein.
These*p wait all upon thee; that thou mayest give them their meat in due season.
That*p thou givest them they gather: thou openest thine hand, they are filled with good.
Thou*p hidest thy face, they are troubled: thou takest away their breath, they die, and return to their dust.
Thou*p sendest forth thy spirit, they are created: and thou renewest the face of the earth.
The*p glory of the Lord*s shall endure for ever: the Lord*s shall rejoice in his works.

I*p will sing unto the Lord*s as long as I live: I will sing praise to my God while I have my being.
My*p meditation of him shall be sweet: I will be glad in the Lord.*s
Let*p the sinners be consumed out of the earth, and let the wicked be no more. Bless thou the Lord,*s O my soul. Praise ye the Lord.*s
